{"id":"1609.02212","submitter":"Molei Tao","authors":"Molei Tao","title":"Explicit symplectic approximation of nonseparable Hamiltonians:\n  algorithm and long time performance","comments":"Accepted by Phys. Rev. E","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 94, 043303 (2016)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.94.043303","report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA math.DS physics.class-ph physics.comp-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Explicit symplectic integrators have been important tools for accurate and\nefficient approximations of mechanical systems with separable Hamiltonians. For\nthe first time, the article proposes for arbitrary Hamiltonians similar\nintegrators, which are explicit, of any even order, symplectic in an extended\nphase space, and with pleasant long time properties. They are based on a\nmechanical restraint that binds two copies of phase space together. Using\nbackward error analysis, KAM theory, and additional multiscale analysis, an\nerror bound of $\\mathcal{O}(T\\delta^l \\omega)$ is established for integrable\nsystems, where $T$, $\\delta$, $l$ and $\\omega$ are respectively the (long)\nsimulation time, step size, integrator order, and some binding constant. For\nnon-integrable systems with positive Lyapunov exponents, such an error bound is\ngenerally impossible, but satisfactory statistical behaviors were observed in a\nnumerical experiment with a nonlinear Schr\\\"{o}dinger equation.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 7 Sep 2016 22:47:24 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-10-19"}
